<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Russell Group Equality Forum (WSC071)_x000b_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Russell Group Equality Forum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (WSC071)</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The following response is from the Russell Group Equality Forum (RGEF). This group consists of Equality and Diversity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">professionals working in the leading research intensive Universities in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Forum does not represent the views of The Russell Group of Universities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do you think the number of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Culture</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gendered stereotypes and biases (conscious and unconscious):</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This is a complex and wide ranging problem that underpins many of the discussions around women in academia. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The impact of these stereotypes and biases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> seen in various ways, including lower representation of women in conference panels/key note speakers, the under-recognition of women (Matilda Effect), and inequitable recruitment or promotion practices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research has highlighted the impact of biases dur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing interviews and peer review processes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These research projects often involve panels being given identical CVs with obviously gendered names. In these studies, women are less likely to be considered of equal standing, less likely to be offered a posi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tion and if they are offered a post they are offered a lower salary than male applicants. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The skills or abilities people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">associate with a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> scientist, leader or a manager are also connected to a normative masculine identity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and women who display these ski</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lls are often judged negatively because they are perceived to be presenting stereotypically masculine traits. Conversely, women who don’t display these traits may be viewed as unsuitable for the role.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This questions the basic assumption of meritocracy tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t pervades academia. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many institutions are starting to deliver</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> unconscious bias</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> training but there can be a lack of take-up</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or engagement </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by those who need it most.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ack of Role Models:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The number of female guest speakers and images of women on display for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> example </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> minimal or non-existent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Women are often not encouraged by peers to network and be at the fore-front of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Department</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Further, there is a distinct lack of successful female role models with families which makes graduates see academia as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">somewhere not to have a successful career and a family.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of support and feelings of isolation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Progression is often supported by senior academics who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> sponsor or informally mentor early c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">areer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">esearchers (ECRs). This can be affected by the gendered con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scious or unconscious biases of senior academics, who are predominantly male. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">senior male academics may be more likely to offer sponsorship to young male ECRs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who, unconsciously, remind them of themselves at an earlier stage in their career, w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hile women may not as frequently be afforded the same informal support and encouragement.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Low visibility and communication of science as a viable career for women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and a lack of encouragement from parents/teachers/media to validate science as a career fo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r girls. This encouragement and communication should be done in a way that will appeal to girls – for example, the recent European Commission campaign ‘Science: it’s a girl thing!’ was heavily criticised for its use of overtly feminine stereotypes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of mobility in dual career relationships</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, which can also impact on the gender pay gap</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Career Development</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Short term contracts: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Post doc positions often have low organisational status, poor rates of basic pay and job insecurity. This is particularly an issue for women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">if</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this period of uncertainty coincides with child-bearing.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of clear career structure/pathway:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aving to do </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a series of fixed term positions before you can start an academic career </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">put women off. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Short term contracts mean that ECRs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are expected </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to move around Universities more often than is ideal, especially for those who wish to stay in one place so that th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ey can raise children. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inconsistent support for career progression: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ecuring a permanent lecturer job can be difficult for post docs, especially if they have little support from their departments or university in preparing their CVs and interviews</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">f mentors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mentoring </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ECRs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is often performed by senior academics on an informal basis. Senior academics are usually male, and either consciously or unconsciously tend to choose people similar to themselves (i.e. males) to mentor.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Competitiveness of fellowship and funding opportunities: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These processes are affected by the biases describe above, and often favour overtly confident men.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women in particular may be put off by this competitive culture and environment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, for example, resea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rch suggests that the attractiveness of an academi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">c career decreases during their PhD</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Relentless competition </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for publications, funding and academic positions which reflects a masculine model of success</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Confidence: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is often suggested that women tak</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e longer to apply for promotion than men – this might be due to confidence levels or feeling the need to cover every criterion before submitting an application. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recognition: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women often take on activities that benefit the University/Department – this migh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t happen through choice, or through gendered biases, for example, the assumed connection between women and a ‘maternal instinct’ can mean women are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">offered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> ‘pastoral roles’. This means that women have less time to focus on activities that would warrant pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">motion. The achievements women do make are usually left unrecognised because women are often too modest and do not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">market themselves. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The biases explained above mean that w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">omen need to ‘outperform’ men to gain appropriate recognition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Positive action:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Women often feel disinclined to engage with discussions if they think they will be further marginalised by others views that they are getting ‘special treatment’ rather than actions to redress historical imbalance. Messages given by Government and Univers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ities need challenge this view and set this work in the wider organisational and social context. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Impact of caring responsibilities</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Barriers to returning to work after maternity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Career progression, for example through publication, funding and collaborations are difficult if you have a career break. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fear of falling behind during maternity leave with science being a fast moving culture</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Childcare options/nursery places and cost</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Long</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> hours culture: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A culture of long working hours is very common in academia, and this can act as a disincentive, or simply not be viable, for women who are the primary carers of young children or older or disabled relatives. Holding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">meeting and seminars </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">out</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">side core hours thus disadvantages scientists with carin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Career progression is often facilitated by an ability to work long hours and travel internationally which may hinder those who have caring responsibilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Insufficient opportuni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ties for part time working and job sharing: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The lack of opportunities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gives the impression that part time working isn’t possible or compatible with an academic career. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Perception of part time/flexible working:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Women often report feeling marginalised when </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">working </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and feel that they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> perceived</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> as no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t fully ‘pulling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> their weight</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There needs to be a culture change which shows the benefits to an organisation from people working flexible hours as well as the challenges.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There needs to be a wider discussion and recognition that this is not just a ‘women’s problem’: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Caring for family mem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bers is increasingly becoming an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">issue for men as well as women. This should be recognised and men should be facilitated to play active rol</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">es as carers for both children and elders. This would serve to balance the responsibilities of caring between genders and a change in attitudes towards these issues, allowing for greater flexibility in careers.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Perception of caring roles:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Often both men an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d women who rise to senior positions are unlikely to have caring responsibilities, either their partners take on this role or individuals have decided not to have children. This gives a message that this is what people need to do in order to rise to senior</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> levels.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Careers women transition into</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women often work in industry or for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a government agency after they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> leave academia.  Alternatively, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women develop careers in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">teaching, accountancy, finance, publishing, administration, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">communications and human resources.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a perception that there is not a healthy work life balance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in academia, and as the pay is much better in industry, this is where women are drawn to.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Vitae, the national career development organisation for researchers, have published a series of reports on ‘What do Researchers do?’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">based on LDLHE (Longitudinal Dest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inations of Leavers in Higher Education) cohorts, as well as labour market information for doctoral researchers, but a longer follow on for LDLHE  (&gt;3 years post PhD), larger cohorts and additional case studies would be useful.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Consequences</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Knowledge prod</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uction and performance:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Science will not reach its full potential if it does not benefit from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> diversity of background</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, opinions and perspectives </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Diversity is the best catalyst for new ideas and innovation and therefore the retention of women in a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cademia is greatly needed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Research also suggests that a higher representation of women at senior management levels has a positive effect on performance </span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Loss of investment:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The investment in women’s training may be lost if routes are not found to enable them to re-enter the workforce after career breaks. Many take jobs which do not use their skills.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of role models:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  The presence of women professors can have a significan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t positive effect on the confidence and self-esteem of female students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is often assumed that graduates have knowledge about career choices, but this is not always the case, as a result career support is needed, including talks from female academics.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Industry will be seen as the natural progression for women (not academia): </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">If students are not able to identify themselves with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">staff at the University they will see academic as somewhere that they do not fit and will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">choose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to work elsewhere. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reinforcin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g stereotypes and biases:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the lack of female scientists will continue to affirm the stereotype that women don’t do science. The image of science as male dominated, and assumptions around who does or doesn’t achieve in science can inform gendered assumption</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s of what is normal or natural for a boy or girl to be interested in – this in turn deters young women and girls from choosing science subjects at school, A level and University. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> graduates and Ph.D students in academic careers? Are there any examples of good practice?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What should Universities and HE sector do?</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improve support at key transition points</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There should be more support for ECRs – particularly those transitioning </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">between PhD, post-doctoral and lectureship posts. More needs to be done to encourage and support female ECRs – both in terms of applications for funding or positions, but also in the security of positions. Universities could look into ways of ensuring secu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rity for post-doctora</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">l fellows.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Career Support:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Clear career advice should be available which is sensitive to diversity and gender and a clear career structure should be provided detailing career </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">options</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> so that individuals can make an informed decision ab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">out their career choice.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">PI Support:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Principal Investigators</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should be better supported to understand and deliver mentoring &amp; career advice. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Networking:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Improve opportunities for networking so graduates/students have the chance to meet </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ECRs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">/lecturers and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hear their stories about how they made the transition from student to staff. Cross-faculty and multi-disciplinary events open more doors across the University.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Role Models:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Showcase and celebrate successful female academics.  Ensure that conferences, sem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inars and events include female speakers wherever possible.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Communication:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Ensure staff and students are aware of the policies in place to help support. Running events where women graduates can see/hear that it is possible to be a mother and an academic an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d highlighting the support available following maternity leave is important. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Empowering women – individually and collectively: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The provision of visible role models and development opportunities for women can help promote careers in academia.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Questioning existing culture and practice. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institutions must ensure that women receive equal and respectful treatment in the workplace, particularly in disciplines where there is a majority of men and/or a culture that disadvantages women. This might inclu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">de training in equality and diversity and fair recruitment policies and unconscious bias might help to draw attention to any issues that need addressing. Making sure that there is a support network for any member of staff who may experience discrimination </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is also important – along with a formal system to tackle such issues. Good practices will benefit male and female ECRs alike, but a failure to address the impact of existing culture and practices will tend to perpetuate the status quo.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Awareness raising of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> gender equality issues:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is important to engage both men and women in the agenda, so that challenges are not seen as women’s issues and can be addressed by both sexes.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Family friendly policies and work-life balance: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities need </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ensure people ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n work flexibly, and that the University has supportive family friendly policies. If we want to encourage and retain women then we need to do more to support those who want to work part-time, flexibly or take a career break and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to challenge assumptions and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> biases around flexible working so that everyone has the opportunity to p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rogress their career.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recruitment:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Universities should look for a new way in measuring the output of an individual, such as normalising by the number of years working in the post, whi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ch takes into consideration part-time work and maternity leave </span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Outreach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> initiatives </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> engage and retain women in STEMM: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is vital that institutions and individuals address sectoral and professional responsibilities in promoting science beyond thei</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r local environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Examples of good practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> from Russell Group universities</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">:</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Networks:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for example, networks of female staff and students in particular Faculties or Schools. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Mentoring and coaching schemes</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘Buddy systems’:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> linking PhD students to PDRAs. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Careers services:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> providing information to all students during and after their studies. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gender representation on interview panels:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at least one third female membership. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recruitment training: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Anyone who sits on an intervie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">w panel has to first attend fair recruitment briefing</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Unconscious bias training:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> rolled out to managers and departmental staff across the University </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Accountability framework:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Faculties have to submit an equality action plan each year and assess their prog</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ress and this is connected to the performance-related pay of senior management</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Springboard training</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sabbatical:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Academics returning from maternity leave are offered a 6 month sabbatical in order to focus on their research and be relieved from teaching resp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">onsibilities </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Diversity training:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is a condition of probation</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Paternity leave</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: extended to 4 weeks (20 days) paid leave</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Returning Carers Fund</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: supports those returning from a period of extended leave (including maternity leave) to get research back on track </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Flexible working policies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: including part time, job share and condensed hours.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Criteria for Senior Academic Promotions to promote gender e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">quality</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Equal Pay information published and findings addressed </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Resourcing:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (staff and funding) to support participation in Athena SWAN at institutional and departmental levels </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">High number of visible female </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">role models</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> via local and national outreach and science communication initiatives (e.g. Soapbox Science, STEMnet, L’Oreal women in science recipients, nationally respected gender equality champion, radio and TV appearances)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sponsorship</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for women returning from a care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">er break (via Daphne Jackson Fellows)</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">National provision of targeted funding to introduce good practice and maintain initiatives to improve the recruitme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nt, retention and promotion of women. For example:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Resourcing of schemes such as the Athena SWAN Charter and Project Juno, and support for universities to engage with and sustain activities to support charter principles</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">National mentoring programmes</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Better</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> funding and support mechanisms to enable returners to get back into the workforce e.g. extending current schemes (e.g. Daphne Jackson Trust) and providing courses to get returners back up to speed/confidence building.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Change in national UK policy regardin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g provision of resources, to ensure all researchers have:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">paid maternity cover (particularly on external grant funding) and that funding rules </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">actively promote equality and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">make it viable to extend grants as appropriate</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increased opportunities for flexible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> working e.g. part-time fellowships</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">National monitoring of:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gender equality across all parts of the Research Council system to ensure elimination of any bias</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">impact of change in paternity leave entitlement, how has this translated into men and women sharing parental leave, so enabling women to re-establish working lives/achieving improved work-life balance </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">collate and analyse existing equality data across the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sector and publish it annually</span></li></ol><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Equalise maternity/paternity pay:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">current statutory provision allows for shared maternity/paternity leave but on different financial terms, which acts as a deterrent/obstacle for men to play an equal part in childcare</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equalising maternity/paternity pay provisions would enable women and men to be treated equally by employers (ie both would be perceived as have potential absences for childcare rather than women being perceived as a risk, as at present) and to have equal a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ccess to career progression opportunities</span></li></ol><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Review post doc positions and short term contracts: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government could encourage the review of the role of post docs and researchers –researchers have suggested that they would be interested in continuing within </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">academia if there were more opportunities for permanent positions, and several have said that they would be interested in a ‘professional post doc’ post. The stress of short fixed term contracts appears to be a huge disincentive for students and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ECRs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">offering more options, or more secure positions might increase interest in an academic career.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Funding Bodies: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Encourage funding bodies to ask for information on equality and diversity as part of the funding applications process.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Moreover, funding bodies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">not only need to consider the actions undertaken by departments to increase the number of underrepresented groups, but also the gender dimension of research</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Funding bodies should be encouraged to consider their own gender balance and representation – for e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">xample in governing bodies/councils, panels and decision making forms. The Equality Challenge Unit if resourced appropriately can play a key role in actively developing these approaches with Universities. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Financial incentives:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Government and research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> funding bodies should set up stand-alone pots of money for universities and departments who can demonstrate sustained progress on gender equality in order to incentivise action and reward success.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Make a clear statement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of expectations for rate of improve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ment in female participation and progression</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Knobloch-Westerwick</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">, S. Glynn, C. J. and Huge, M. 2013.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> The Matilda Effect in Science Communication: An Experiment on Gender Bias in Publication Quality Perceptions and Collaboration Interest</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Science Communication.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> pp.1-23.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Moss-Racusin</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">, C. A.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> et. al. 2012</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">. Sc